00:15:32,280 --> 00:15:33,640
I did not expect anything

263
00:15:33,640 --> 00:15:36,400
because it was only a change in Python.

264
00:15:36,400 --> 00:15:39,560
And many people who don't know anything about Python

265
00:15:39,560 --> 00:15:42,520
started to discuss this thing.

266
00:15:42,520 --> 00:15:47,520
But it's just to give you an example of the diversity issues.

267
00:15:50,080 --> 00:15:53,780
Okay, we saw the problems, so let's see the solutions.

268
00:15:54,680 --> 00:15:58,120
First of all, as I said, it's not a technical issue,

269
00:15:58,120 --> 00:15:59,600
it's a human issue.

270
00:15:59,600 --> 00:16:00,920
So you need a different tool.

271
00:16:01,320 --> 00:16:03,120
You cannot use a debugger,

272
00:16:03,120 --> 00:16:06,200
but what you can do is, for example, psychology.

273
00:16:06,200 --> 00:16:09,480
And there is something called the unconscious biases.

274
00:16:10,360 --> 00:16:14,040
They are social stereotypes about certain group of people

275
00:16:14,040 --> 00:16:16,720
that individuals forms outside their mind

276
00:16:18,280 --> 00:16:21,720
outside their own conscious awareness.

277
00:16:21,720 --> 00:16:24,520
So it's a little bit tricky to understand it,

278
00:16:24,520 --> 00:16:28,960
but the key point is that there are biases

279
00:16:28,960 --> 00:16:30,680
and you are not aware of them.

280
00:16:31,440 --> 00:16:34,920
It means that even if you are trying to not be racist,

281
00:16:34,920 --> 00:16:39,840
to not have stereotypes, you still have stereotypes.

282
00:16:40,920 --> 00:16:44,200
And I found a good example to explain you that

283
00:16:46,000 --> 00:16:48,160
today we have more and more machine learning

284
00:16:48,160 --> 00:16:51,440
and some people decided to apply machine learning

285
00:16:51,440 --> 00:16:54,540
to the justice to help to take decision.

286
00:16:56,120 --> 00:16:59,120
And a study has been made on the machine learning

287
00:16:59,120 --> 00:17:01,440
used to predict future crime.

288
00:17:01,440 --> 00:17:03,880
And the study says that the machine learning

289
00:17:03,880 --> 00:17:07,040
is biased against black people.

290
00:17:07,040 --> 00:17:10,560
So this is just one example of two people

291
00:17:10,560 --> 00:17:15,200
who have been arrested because they possessed drug.

292
00:17:15,200 --> 00:17:18,800
And the white person got a score of three,

293
00:17:18,800 --> 00:17:20,440
which is low risk.

294
00:17:20,440 --> 00:17:24,400
And the black person got a score of 10, which is high risk.

295
00:17:24,400 --> 00:17:27,240
But the machine learning failed

296
00:17:27,280 --> 00:17:32,280
because the white person has been arrested three more times

297
00:17:32,360 --> 00:17:35,160
and the black person has not been arrested after that.

298
00:17:37,880 --> 00:17:40,840
And machine learning, to try to simplify

299
00:17:40,840 --> 00:17:45,840
as much as possible, you have data, you have the training,

300
00:17:46,520 --> 00:17:49,020
and from that you get prediction.

301
00:17:49,020 --> 00:17:51,840
So if the prediction is racist,

302
00:17:51,840 --> 00:17:55,800
maybe the issue is coming from your input data.

303
00:17:56,720 --> 00:18:01,360
And what I'm trying to say is that thanks to software,

304
00:18:01,360 --> 00:18:04,760
we can look at ourself inside a mirror

305
00:18:04,760 --> 00:18:07,000
and we can see that we are racist.

306
00:18:07,000 --> 00:18:08,200
It's part of us.

307
00:18:08,200 --> 00:18:13,200
It's just that the software is telling us that we are racist.

308
00:18:15,200 --> 00:18:19,080
Something else which is helpful to understand

309
00:18:19,080 --> 00:18:23,440
the human relationship and how people behave

310
00:18:23,440 --> 00:18:26,120
is called the imposter syndrome.

311
00:18:26,120 --> 00:18:29,160
It's a psychological pattern in which an individual

312
00:18:29,160 --> 00:18:31,120
doubts their accomplishments

313
00:18:31,120 --> 00:18:34,880
and has a persistent internalized fear

314
00:18:34,880 --> 00:18:37,000
of being exposed as a fraud.

315
00:18:37,880 --> 00:18:41,960
So again, it's not really easy to understand what it means.

316
00:18:43,160 --> 00:18:47,440
To explain it differently, I would say that you consider

317
00:18:47,440 --> 00:18:49,440
that you don't deserve what you get.

318
00:18:49,440 --> 00:18:54,440
And I think a good example of the imposter syndrome

319
00:18:54,440 --> 00:18:57,120
is that nowadays more and more people

320
00:18:57,120 --> 00:19:01,120
are using the social media, social networks.

321
00:19:01,960 --> 00:19:05,240
And the thing is that when you go to these websites,

322
00:19:05,240 --> 00:19:09,040
people are only sharing the best of themselves.

323
00:19:09,040 --> 00:19:14,040
They try to share photos of their latest amazing travel,

324
00:19:14,120 --> 00:19:18,120
of their beautiful children, of their children,

325
00:19:18,360 --> 00:19:22,240
of their funny pictures of cats.

326
00:19:22,240 --> 00:19:26,360
And when you look at all of this, slowly you consider

327
00:19:26,360 --> 00:19:28,680
that your life is less interesting

328
00:19:28,680 --> 00:19:30,520
than the life of your friends

329
00:19:30,520 --> 00:19:32,760
because you compare your life to the life

330
00:19:32,760 --> 00:19:35,440
of people using the social media.

331
00:19:36,640 --> 00:19:40,680
And because of that, some therapists started to say

332
00:19:40,680 --> 00:19:44,080
that the social media are making us more depressed.

333
00:19:45,080 --> 00:19:49,960
And the thing is that this is one example

334
00:19:49,960 --> 00:19:52,000
of the imposter syndrome because you consider

335
00:19:52,000 --> 00:19:55,080
that your life is less interesting.

336
00:19:55,080 --> 00:19:58,840
It's just because social media are designed

337
00:19:58,840 --> 00:20:02,880
to make people only share the best of themselves

338
00:20:02,880 --> 00:20:05,680
to only share the positive message.

339
00:20:05,680 --> 00:20:08,400
When someone is sick in your family,

340
00:20:08,400 --> 00:20:12,080
if you get a very boring day,

341
00:20:12,080 --> 00:20:14,280
nobody shares this kind of information

342
00:20:14,280 --> 00:20:16,000
because it's boring.

343
00:20:16,880 --> 00:20:20,000
And I think that we can also make the parallel with work

344
00:20:20,000 --> 00:20:23,600
because it's common that as war people just show

345
00:20:23,600 --> 00:20:28,440
the best of themselves and they try to hide their defects

346
00:20:28,440 --> 00:20:31,040
just because we want to get a promotion,

347
00:20:31,040 --> 00:20:35,680
we want to show that we are very good at what we are doing.

348
00:20:35,680 --> 00:20:39,960
But when you compare yourself to your peers,

349
00:20:39,960 --> 00:20:42,600
you consider that your work is less valuable

350
00:20:42,600 --> 00:20:43,720
just because of that.

351
00:20:49,040 --> 00:20:51,200
Now let's talk about the code of conduct.

352
00:20:52,640 --> 00:20:55,720
So at the beginning, there was no code of conduct.

353
00:20:58,560 --> 00:21:00,800
And it was fine at the beginning

354
00:21:00,800 --> 00:21:05,360
because Python was quite small with a few people,

355
00:21:05,360 --> 00:21:08,600
but slowly Python becomes more and more popular

356
00:21:08,600 --> 00:21:12,640
and we started to see some conflicts between people.

357
00:21:12,640 --> 00:21:16,320
And we say that maybe we need some kind of agreements

358
00:21:16,320 --> 00:21:18,600
of what is a good behavior

359
00:21:18,600 --> 00:21:21,320
and what is an inappropriate behavior.

360
00:21:22,720 --> 00:21:25,120
So code of conduct has been created

361
00:21:25,120 --> 00:21:29,520
and first it has been applied on the mailing list

362
00:21:29,520 --> 00:21:32,880
to continue with the bug tracker and also the websites.

363
00:21:33,920 --> 00:21:38,040
Now the code of conduct is also applied to conferences

364
00:21:38,040 --> 00:21:39,480
like back in US.

365
00:21:40,640 --> 00:21:44,640
And last year, the back in US even used the service

366
00:21:44,640 --> 00:21:48,640
of a company to help to manage code of conduct incidents

367
00:21:48,640 --> 00:21:51,200
because the worst thing that you want to get

368
00:21:51,200 --> 00:21:53,800
in case of code of conduct incidents

369
00:21:53,800 --> 00:21:56,480
is to make the event even worse.

370
00:21:56,480 --> 00:22:00,640
So you have to be able to understand what is the issue,

371
00:22:00,640 --> 00:22:04,280
how to provide the best action

372
00:22:04,280 --> 00:22:07,440
and to be able to react quickly.

373
00:22:07,480 --> 00:22:10,200
So this is not something that we are used to do

374
00:22:10,200 --> 00:22:12,280
and we need some training for that.

375
00:22:14,040 --> 00:22:16,440
And by the way, the Python Software Foundation

376
00:22:16,440 --> 00:22:19,040
even requires a code of conduct

377
00:22:19,040 --> 00:22:22,040
for all conferences called PyCon.

378
00:22:23,200 --> 00:22:25,120
And now the discussion is more about

379
00:22:25,120 --> 00:22:29,160
how to handle incidents and bans

380
00:22:29,160 --> 00:22:30,840
to be blocked on our community.

381
00:22:32,680 --> 00:22:35,720
Some people propose to maybe write down some rules,

382
00:22:35,760 --> 00:22:39,400
but it's a little bit tricky to agree on that.

383
00:22:41,440 --> 00:22:43,160
To come back to the diversity,

384
00:22:44,760 --> 00:22:47,520
the diversity means different things.

385
00:22:47,520 --> 00:22:49,880
And for example, you can see that

386
00:22:49,880 --> 00:22:52,120
as a diversity of point of view

387
00:22:52,120 --> 00:22:54,000
because in Python some people cares more

388
00:22:54,000 --> 00:22:56,040
about the documentation,

389
00:22:56,040 --> 00:22:58,920
some others about the reference counting in C

390
00:22:58,920 --> 00:23:00,800
or the backward compatibility,

391
00:23:00,800 --> 00:23:03,400
the API, the language consistency,

392
00:23:05,800 --> 00:23:08,560
ability to find the simplest solution,

393
00:23:08,560 --> 00:23:10,680
to care about corner cases,

394
00:23:10,680 --> 00:23:12,520
performance, security,

395
00:23:12,520 --> 00:23:15,520
other Python implementation like PyPy.

396
00:23:15,520 --> 00:23:18,160
And if you take a small group of people

397
00:23:18,160 --> 00:23:21,600
who are only experts on certain area,

398
00:23:21,600 --> 00:23:25,400
maybe Python wouldn't be as good as it is today.

399
00:23:25,400 --> 00:23:28,560
We really need this diversity of point of view

400
00:23:28,560 --> 00:23:31,960
to make Python as good as it can be.

401
00:23:32,960 --> 00:23:36,120
It can also means the diversity of use cases

402
00:23:36,120 --> 00:23:37,840
because some people are using Python

403
00:23:37,840 --> 00:23:40,320
for command line interface.

404
00:23:40,320 --> 00:23:44,240
And in that case, what is important is a startup time.

405
00:23:44,240 --> 00:23:45,880
And some people are using Python

406
00:23:45,880 --> 00:23:48,320
for several running for multiple days.

407
00:23:48,320 --> 00:23:52,480
And here what is important is more the memory usage

408
00:23:52,480 --> 00:23:55,000
because you don't want to have to reboot your server

409
00:23:55,000 --> 00:23:56,680
because it's out of memory.

410
00:23:57,640 --> 00:24:00,680
Some people are using the graphical interfaces

411
00:24:00,680 --> 00:24:05,320
for machine learning, develop rest servers,

412
00:24:05,320 --> 00:24:08,320
games, and many other use cases.

413
00:24:09,880 --> 00:24:13,200
To give you a very concrete example of what I said,

414
00:24:13,200 --> 00:24:15,920
Naoki Inada has been promoted as a core developer

415
00:24:15,920 --> 00:24:17,640
three years ago.

416
00:24:17,640 --> 00:24:21,360
And he has been selected as a BDFL delegate.

417
00:24:21,360 --> 00:24:24,080
So the one to take the decision on a PEP.

418
00:24:24,080 --> 00:24:28,240
For the PEP 538, which is a C local question,

419
00:24:28,480 --> 00:24:33,240
and my PEP 340, which is a UTF-8 mode.

420
00:24:34,480 --> 00:24:38,160
And what we can see is that in fact,

421
00:24:38,160 --> 00:24:40,800
English speakers are just satisfied with ASCII

422
00:24:40,800 --> 00:24:44,800
because it's plenty enough to write

423
00:24:44,800 --> 00:24:46,640
whatever you want in English.

424
00:24:46,640 --> 00:24:49,920
But maybe people from Japan are more used

425
00:24:49,920 --> 00:24:51,520
to Unicode issues.

426
00:24:51,520 --> 00:24:55,900
So it's something which are really bugging them every day.

427
00:24:55,900 --> 00:24:58,220
And for Naoki Inada, it's really important

428
00:24:59,220 --> 00:25:02,100
to make sure that Python is working in all cases

429
00:25:02,100 --> 00:25:03,780
for any kind of encoding.

430
00:25:06,820 --> 00:25:09,640
Okay, now let's see the mentoring.

431
00:25:09,640 --> 00:25:13,140
And I would like to begin with the positive actions.

432
00:25:13,140 --> 00:25:17,700
So three years ago at the SpyCon,

433
00:25:17,700 --> 00:25:19,660
Willow Van Rossum encouraged women

434
00:25:19,660 --> 00:25:21,860
to contact him for mentoring.

435
00:25:21,860 --> 00:25:24,060
And he mentored Marjata Vijaya,

436
00:25:24,060 --> 00:25:27,180
who became the first woman core developer

437
00:25:27,220 --> 00:25:29,340
in January 2017.

438
00:25:31,620 --> 00:25:35,540
And after Marjata, other women have been promoted,

439
00:25:35,540 --> 00:25:37,580
Carol Winning, Lisa Roach,

440
00:25:37,580 --> 00:25:40,860
Emily Morehouse, and Sheryl Sibala.

441
00:25:40,860 --> 00:25:43,780
And you can see that thanks to positive action,

442
00:25:43,780 --> 00:25:47,100
we moved from zero woman core developers

443
00:25:47,100 --> 00:25:50,620
up to five woman core developers.

444
00:25:50,620 --> 00:25:55,520
So it's still not 50-50, but at least it's growing.

445
00:25:57,740 --> 00:26:00,140
And to explain you the mentoring,

446
00:26:00,140 --> 00:26:03,180
I would like to come back to the beginning of my journey

447
00:26:03,180 --> 00:26:04,660
about the burnouts.

448
00:26:04,660 --> 00:26:07,080
I say that I don't care.

449
00:26:07,080 --> 00:26:11,740
So the idea of mentoring is that instead of fixing an issue,

450
00:26:11,740 --> 00:26:15,540
you have to explain it to how to fix it.

451
00:26:15,540 --> 00:26:18,180
Or say differently, give a man a fish

452
00:26:18,180 --> 00:26:20,500
and you feed him for a day.

453
00:26:20,500 --> 00:26:25,080
Teach a man to fish and you feed him for a lifetime.

454
00:26:26,080 --> 00:26:29,760
For example, I mentored Pablo Salgado

455
00:26:29,760 --> 00:26:33,320
between January and June 2018.

456
00:26:33,320 --> 00:26:36,080
And he became a core developer in June.

457
00:26:36,080 --> 00:26:40,540
And usually it's way, way longer to become a core developer.

458
00:26:40,540 --> 00:26:44,000
So what I'm trying to say is that thanks to mentoring,

459
00:26:44,000 --> 00:26:47,820
it was possible for him to become a core developer.

460
00:26:47,820 --> 00:26:49,560
Or maybe without mentoring,

461
00:26:49,560 --> 00:26:52,640
he would just move to another project

462
00:26:52,640 --> 00:26:55,220
or stop contributing to Python.

463
00:26:57,360 --> 00:26:59,520
And you have to understand that the development

464
00:26:59,520 --> 00:27:01,920
of an open source project like Python

465
00:27:01,920 --> 00:27:04,480
is really a matter of trust.

466
00:27:04,480 --> 00:27:07,240
To be able to give the keys of Python,

467
00:27:07,240 --> 00:27:09,360
to give the commit bit of Python,

468
00:27:09,360 --> 00:27:13,640
you really need a very, very high level of confidence

469
00:27:13,640 --> 00:27:15,520
in someone you have to trust

470
00:27:15,520 --> 00:27:17,740
as the person that you are promoting.

471
00:27:18,740 --> 00:27:22,560
Python is also about communities.

472
00:27:26,140 --> 00:27:28,300
You have, for example, PyLadies.

473
00:27:28,300 --> 00:27:32,420
And their module is women who love coding in Python.

474
00:27:32,420 --> 00:27:36,020
They are organizing events all around the world.

475
00:27:36,020 --> 00:27:40,060
As there are events in Australia, Brazil, France, India,

476
00:27:40,060 --> 00:27:42,620
Netherlands, Nigeria, Taiwan.

477
00:27:42,620 --> 00:27:44,880
And their website is PyLadies.com.

478
00:27:45,800 --> 00:27:47,800
This is the kind of thing that they do,

479
00:27:47,800 --> 00:27:52,800
is to organize events to teach Python to women.

480
00:27:53,400 --> 00:27:54,840
But you can see in the audience

481
00:27:54,840 --> 00:27:58,960
that it's not only for women, it's also for men.

482
00:28:01,040 --> 00:28:03,200
There is trans or code.

